 this whole auto increment thing,

253
00:12:02,220 --> 00:12:05,380
 that says, hey database, I'm gonna put your records in,

254
00:12:05,380 --> 00:12:06,980
 I'm gonna give you the name and the email,

255
00:12:06,980 --> 00:12:09,940
 and you come up with a number, but then when you're done,

256
00:12:09,940 --> 00:12:12,420
 I want you to tell me what the number is,

257
00:12:12,420 --> 00:12:14,260
 and this is how you get that number,

258
00:12:14,260 --> 00:12:16,020
 by saying, oh, print u.id.

259
00:12:16,020 --> 00:12:18,740
 Now if you printed u.id before you did the save,

260
00:12:18,740 --> 00:12:21,620
 it wouldn't exist, and then print u.email,

261
00:12:21,620 --> 00:12:24,260
 you can see this email is just the data we put in,

262
00:12:24,260 --> 00:12:29,260
 but now this is not only in your u variable,

263
00:12:29,260 --> 00:12:31,980
 but it's also in the database as well, okay?

264
00:12:31,980 --> 00:12:38,420
 Now, we can dig a little bit into

265
00:12:38,420 --> 00:12:41,340
 how this object relational mapping is working,

266
00:12:41,340 --> 00:12:43,340
 and so if you're in the middle,

267
00:12:43,340 --> 00:12:45,420
 you're doing things like that last statement,

268
00:12:45,420 --> 00:12:49,300
 you can, from Django DB import connection,

269
00:12:49,300 --> 00:12:51,220
 and then ask connection.queries,

270
00:12:51,220 --> 00:12:52,860
 and then what it does is it just shows you

271
00:12:52,860 --> 00:12:55,660
 a little bit of debug data, and what it did,

272
00:12:55,660 --> 00:12:58,820
 how it started, the fact that it ran an insert statement,

273
00:12:58,820 --> 00:13:00,980
 and again, this looks kind of familiar,

274
00:13:00,980 --> 00:13:04,940
 it's making up SQL for you for that insert,

275
00:13:04,940 --> 00:13:07,720
 the save statement, right, that save statement there,

276
00:13:07,720 --> 00:13:10,100
 it's making that insert for you,

277
00:13:10,100 --> 00:13:13,580
 and then you can actually see what it's doing, right?

278
00:13:13,580 --> 00:13:17,060
 And so this save, you know, set up a thing and save it,

279
00:13:17,060 --> 00:13:18,900
 you don't need to know insert into or whatever,

280
00:13:18,900 --> 00:13:21,780
 'cause the object relational model does it for you, right?

281
00:13:21,780 --> 00:13:23,660
 And this is kind of what we did before,

282
00:13:23,660 --> 00:13:26,340
 insert into capital users by hand.

283
00:13:26,340 --> 00:13:30,180
 And so again, you know, you'll find this ORM

284
00:13:30,180 --> 00:13:31,860
 is gonna save you a whole bunch of time

285
00:13:31,860 --> 00:13:34,660
 for 80% of the things that you do with the database.

286
00:13:34,660 --> 00:13:38,440
 And so you can do basic CRUD operations

287
00:13:38,440 --> 00:13:40,760
 with this object relational mapper.

288
00:13:40,760 --> 00:13:45,980
 The save is the insert, you can select,

289
00:13:45,980 --> 00:13:49,460
 is basically user object values,

290
00:13:49,460 --> 00:13:53,220
 that's like select star, so give me all of the objects.

291
00:13:53,220 --> 00:13:56,660
 A where clause is user objects filter,

292
00:13:56,660 --> 00:13:58,140
 and there's your where clause.

293
00:13:58,140 --> 00:13:59,900
 This is a, email's a column name,

294
00:13:59,900 --> 00:14:03,100
 and csev@umich.edu is a value in that column.

295
00:14:03,100 --> 00:14:05,140
 Values is actually go get 'em,

296
00:14:05,140 --> 00:14:07,540
 so you can create kind of a query,

297
00:14:07,540 --> 00:14:09,440
 so if you don't put values on,

298
00:14:09,440 --> 00:14:12,300
 you get sort of a query that's not yet executed,

299
00:14:12,300 --> 00:14:14,860
 and then values says go do it, do it now.

300
00:14:20,260 --> 00:14:23,220
 So you can do a different, you can delete something,

301
00:14:23,220 --> 00:14:25,580
 where you say, and so this is a little different syntax,

302
00:14:25,580 --> 00:14:28,140
 this is kind of a selector that says

303
00:14:28,140 --> 00:14:29,840
 these are the variables to select,

304
00:14:29,840 --> 00:14:32,620
 and .delete says, I mean the rows to select,

305
00:14:32,620 --> 00:14:34,500
 and then delete those rows.

306
00:14:34,500 --> 00:14:36,100
 So value says retrieve the rows,

307
00:14:36,100 --> 00:14:38,140
 delete says get rid of the rows,

308
00:14:38,140 --> 00:14:40,460
 and then you can, again, the same kind of thing,

309
00:14:40,460 --> 00:14:41,700
 this is kind of like a where clause,

310
00:14:41,700 --> 00:14:45,740
 user objects filter email equals csev@umich.edu.update,

311
00:14:45,740 --> 00:14:48,460
 and then change this column in a way,

312
00:14:48,460 --> 00:14:51,500
 and you can go retrieve all the values,

313
00:14:51,500 --> 00:14:55,140
 and there are things that correspond to lots of the SQL,

314
00:14:55,140 --> 00:14:58,780
 like give me all these values, order by email,

315
00:14:58,780 --> 00:14:59,840
 et cetera, et cetera, et cetera.

316
00:14:59,840 --> 00:15:04,460
 So it's kind of a one-to-one mapping,

317
00:15:04,460 --> 00:15:08,660
 and you will, again, you're gonna do a lot of programming

318
00:15:08,660 --> 00:15:12,020
 using this ORM in Django,

319
00:15:12,020 --> 00:15:14,500
 and every once in a while you'll sneak down to SQL,

320
00:15:14,500 --> 00:15:18,340
 and that's why I sort of teach you the SQL first,

321
00:15:18,340 --> 00:15:20,660
 and there's lots and lots of fields

322
00:15:20,660 --> 00:15:23,480
 that might not actually be represented

323
00:15:23,480 --> 00:15:26,820
 exactly the same way in the database.

324
00:15:26,820 --> 00:15:29,020
 So for example, an email field.

325
00:15:29,020 --> 00:15:31,560
 Databases commonly don't have email fields.

326
00:15:31,560 --> 00:15:33,240
 There might be some databases that have emails,

327
00:15:33,240 --> 00:15:34,660
 and others that don't,

328
00:15:34,660 --> 00:15:36,420
 but because the object-relational mapper

329
00:15:36,420 --> 00:15:38,780
 is a layer between you and the database,

330
00:15:38,780 --> 00:15:41,460
 and you say I'd like this to be an email field,

331
00:15:41,460 --> 00:15:43,260
 then it can add rules and stuff,

332
00:15:43,260 --> 00:15:46,060
 like validity checking, et cetera,

333
00:15:46,060 --> 00:15:48,660
 to say you know what, that doesn't look like an email address.

334
00:15:48,660 --> 00:15:50,220
 And so there's all of these things,

335
00:15:50,220 --> 00:15:52,820
 and these are very useful.

336
00:15:52,820 --> 00:15:55,260
 And later we'll talk about connecting tables,

337
00:15:55,260 --> 00:15:56,820
 and we'll use things like foreign keys,

338
00:15:56,820 --> 00:15:59,540
 and many-to-many fields, and one-to-one fields,

339
00:15:59,540 --> 00:16:02,440
 and those are more, those are less about the data,

340
00:16:02,440 --> 00:16:04,600
 and more about the connections between tables,

341
00:16:04,600 --> 00:16:07,420
 which we'll talk in coming up soon.

342
00:16:07,420 --> 00:16:11,520
 And so just to give you sort of a bit of a sense

343
00:16:11,520 --> 00:16:16,120
 of where you're at, this is our application, right,

344
00:16:16,120 --> 00:16:17,820
 and so we have a browser on the left-hand side

345
00:16:17,820 --> 00:16:20,740
 with a user doing some clicking.

346
00:16:20,740 --> 00:16:23,980
 By now you may have created a urls.py file,

347
00:16:23,980 --> 00:16:27,360
 and that takes the syntax of the get request,

348
00:16:27,360 --> 00:16:30,100
 slash this, slash that, slash whatever,

349
00:16:30,100 --> 00:16:31,780
 and routes it to a particular view

350
00:16:31,780 --> 00:16:34,100
 coming from the views.py file.

351
00:16:34,100 --> 00:16:36,700
 You may or may not have made one of those.

352
00:16:36,700 --> 00:16:40,220
 Templates and forms help produce output,

353
00:16:40,220 --> 00:16:42,500
 but the models are our interaction

354
00:16:42,500 --> 00:16:44,280
 between us and the database.

355
00:16:44,280 --> 00:16:46,840
 And so the actual code we write in Django

356
00:16:46,840 --> 00:16:49,820
 can talk through the models to the database,

357
00:16:49,820 --> 00:16:51,060
 which you may not have done yet,

358
00:16:51,060 --> 00:16:53,900
 but this shell is talking through the Django models

359
00:16:53,900 --> 00:16:55,580
 to the database as well.

360
00:16:55,580 --> 00:16:58,200
 And if you're starting to use the admin user interface,

361
00:16:58,200 --> 00:17:00,900
 the admin user interface talks to the database

362
00:17:00,900 --> 00:17:03,940
 to the models, and it's informed by the kind of things

363
00:17:03,940 --> 00:17:06,060
 that you add to admin.py.

364
00:17:06,060 --> 00:17:08,340
 If you want to use the Django admin interface

365
00:17:08,340 --> 00:17:11,100
 and have your model shown a particular way,

366
00:17:11,100 --> 00:17:12,180
 it's got a bunch of defaults,

367
00:17:12,180 --> 00:17:14,220
 but often you want to override those defaults,

368
00:17:14,220 --> 00:17:15,780
 and so that's what you put in.

369
00:17:15,780 --> 00:17:19,420
 And the model.py file informs this connection

370
00:17:19,420 --> 00:17:20,460
 between the database,

371
00:17:20,460 --> 00:17:22,860
 and it also sort of informs the kind of code

372
00:17:22,860 --> 00:17:25,980
 you write here in a view code, in Python,

373
00:17:25,980 --> 00:17:27,620
 or in the Python shell.

374
00:17:27,620 --> 00:17:29,740
 That's kind of the Django shell,

375
00:17:29,740 --> 00:17:34,540
 which is a Python shell with all that stuff added to it.

376
00:17:34,540 --> 00:17:37,020
 Okay, so this model.py is critical

377
00:17:37,020 --> 00:17:40,680
 to defining our relationship between all of our Python code

378
00:17:40,680 --> 00:17:44,860
 and the admin user interface and the actual database.

379
00:17:44,860 --> 00:17:49,860
 And so you'll see a recorded demo

380
00:17:49,860 --> 00:17:51,780
 where I go through a bunch of those things,

381
00:17:51,780 --> 00:17:52,940
 which I kind of just showed you.

382
00:17:52,940 --> 00:17:55,340
 It's just actually doing it in a demo form,

383
00:17:55,340 --> 00:17:57,580
 but it's all mostly in this lecture.

384
00:17:57,580 --> 00:18:01,100
 And so the Django model is Django's version

385
00:18:01,100 --> 00:18:03,500
 of an object-relational mapper.

386
00:18:03,500 --> 00:18:06,580
 You can write Python code after a while,

387
00:18:06,580 --> 00:18:09,480
 especially if you have an IDE

388
00:18:09,480 --> 00:18:11,860
 that can show you what objects have and stuff.

389
00:18:11,860 --> 00:18:13,500
 You tender, it's a lot easier to write,

390
00:18:13,500 --> 00:18:15,940
 whereas SQL, you have to know it and write it.

391
00:18:15,940 --> 00:18:19,380
 You gain database portability.

392
00:18:19,380 --> 00:18:20,860
 You can create these migrations

393
00:18:20,860 --> 00:18:23,700
 to both build your initial schema in your database

394
00:18:23,700 --> 00:18:26,420
 and then evolve that schema as your application evolves.

395
00:18:26,420 --> 00:18:28,100
 That's one of the more valuable things.

396
00:18:28,100 --> 00:18:30,460
 If you're building straight up SQL,

397
00:18:30,460 --> 00:18:32,340
 going from version one of your database

398
00:18:32,340 --> 00:18:33,620
 to version two of your database,

399
00:18:33,620 --> 00:18:37,000
 it is kind of frustrating and difficult.

400
00:18:37,000 --> 00:18:40,280
 Sometime migrating and evolving a database

401
00:18:40,280 --> 00:18:41,420
 is harder than actually writing

402
00:18:41,420 --> 00:18:43,420
 the SQL code in the first place.

403
00:18:43,420 --> 00:18:44,980
 And Django gives you right out of the box

404
00:18:44,980 --> 00:18:47,120
 this really cool administrator interface.

405
00:18:47,120 --> 00:18:52,040
 The models.py and admin.py will inform that.

406
00:18:52,040 --> 00:18:53,460
 And later we're gonna have all this

407
00:18:53,460 --> 00:18:54,660
 automatic form generation.

408
00:18:54,660 --> 00:18:57,180
 And so what we're doing here is it seems like

409
00:18:57,180 --> 00:18:59,380
 we put like three lines of code into some file

410
00:18:59,380 --> 00:19:01,180
 and then a whole bunch of magic happens.

411
00:19:01,180 --> 00:19:03,140
 And that's really how Django works.

412
00:19:03,140 --> 00:19:05,580
 And the idea is that way you as the developer

413
00:19:05,580 --> 00:19:08,440
 can focus on the columns of your database

414
00:19:08,440 --> 00:19:10,060
 and the forms that you wanna put up

415
00:19:10,060 --> 00:19:13,820
 and spend less and less time sort of manually building

416
00:19:13,820 --> 00:19:18,380
 HTML that's very sort of brittle

417
00:19:18,380 --> 00:19:21,260
 and SQL that's less brittle but still brittle.

418
00:19:21,260 --> 00:19:22,460
 And so that's the idea.

419
00:19:22,460 --> 00:19:25,420
 And so it's a little hard when you're getting started

420
00:19:25,420 --> 00:19:28,900
 because the amount of code you write is so small

421
00:19:28,900 --> 00:19:32,380
 and what that accomplishes is so great.

422
00:19:32,380 --> 00:19:34,700
 But after a while when you get all these little tiny pieces

423
00:19:34,700 --> 00:19:37,380
 figured out then all of a sudden you're like okay

424
00:19:37,380 --> 00:19:39,480
 now I wanna solve that end user's problem

425
00:19:39,480 --> 00:19:41,420
 and you can spend all your time solving that problem

426
00:19:41,420 --> 00:19:43,020
 rather than just making databases

427
00:19:43,020 --> 00:19:44,260
 and those kinds of things.

428
00:19:44,260 --> 00:19:48,220
 So see you in the next lecture.

429
00:19:48,220 --> 00:19:49,060
 Cheers.

430
00:19:49,060 --> 00:19:51,640
 (upbeat music)

